<span id="freeTextContainer9432675824122596165">The darkest, most realist, and best (in my opinion) of Bradshaw&apos;s Down the Long Wind trilogy. Unlike the earlier two novels, magic hardly makes an appearance here, and the focus is not on Gwalchmai (the Gawain character) but on the classic Arthurian love triangle, and the downfall of Arthur&apos;s kingdom. Gwynhwyfar (Guinevere) is narrator and protagonist, and the most well developed character. Being a history wonk, one of the things I appreciate about Bradshaw&apos;s novels is that she is meticulous in </span>
  <span id="freeText9432675824122596165" style="display:none">The darkest, most realist, and best (in my opinion) of Bradshaw's Down the Long Wind trilogy. Unlike the earlier two novels, magic hardly makes an appearance here, and the focus is not on Gwalchmai (the Gawain character) but on the classic Arthurian love triangle, and the downfall of Arthur's kingdom. Gwynhwyfar (Guinevere) is narrator and protagonist, and the most well developed character. Being a history wonk, one of the things I appreciate about Bradshaw's novels is that she is meticulous in her timeline, even though she gives no absolute dates (although it is possible to make a good guess as to what they are.)</span>
