<div id="review_179866449" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/179866449" />
    <a title="Melanti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3034846-melanti"><img alt="Melanti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1286146966p2/3034846.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/179866449?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melanti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melanti" href="/user/show/3034846-melanti">Melanti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12966168-in-winter-s-shadow">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3034846-melanti?shelf=e-book">e-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3034846-melanti?shelf=2014">2014</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer179866449" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7164746613005370472">Reading the conclusion of any series about King Arthur and Camelot is a rather daunting prospect - even more so when you are reading a version from Queen Guinevere&apos;s point of view. <br/><br/>I&apos;m hiding the rest of the review under a spoiler tag because it technically is a spoiler if you&apos;re not already familiar with the legends, but the story is so well known I can&apos;t be bothered to separate the spoiler bits from the safe bits.<br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[<br/><br/>It&apos;s the most famous and tragic case of adultery in western mythos</span></span>
  <span id="freeText7164746613005370472" style="display:none">Reading the conclusion of any series about King Arthur and Camelot is a rather daunting prospect - even more so when you are reading a version from Queen Guinevere's point of view. <br /><br />I'm hiding the rest of the review under a spoiler tag because it technically is a spoiler if you're not already familiar with the legends, but the story is so well known I can't be bothered to separate the spoiler bits from the safe bits.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /><br />It's the most famous and tragic case of adultery in western mythos, IMO. Two people, who should have been loyal to their king, betray him at a devastating cost to those directly involved and to their nation as a whole. There's no way that any decent rendition of the story that even pretends to stay true to the legend can have a happy ending.<br /><br />Bradshaw's version is particularly tragic, IMO. Many authors try to soften the weight of Guinevere's betrayal - making her a casualty of a loveless, arranged marriage or so struck by love at first sight for Lancelot that she just couldn't help herself. But Gwynhwyfar and Bedwyr's affair (Bradshaw conflates Lancelot and Bedwyr) isn't a case of star crossed lovers or a case of an unhappy marriage. She's very much in love with Arthur and Bedwyr is loyal to him as well. They just let their need for comforting each other get away from them, and once those doors have opened, they just can't seem to close them again no matter how much they love and respect the king or what the consequences might be.<br /><br />It seems like a garden variety of adultery - which makes it all the more tragic, IMO. Arthur, the Knights, Camelot, and all of Brittan sacrificed because of a little lack of self control.<br /><br />It occurrs to me that this trilogy, in many ways, is the story of Gwalchmai (Gawain) and his family. In the "spring" book you get Gwalchmai in his rise to fame in the court. In the "summer" book you have Gwalchamai and Agravain killing their wicked sorceress mother Morgawse, leaving their half-brother Medraut (Mordred) at loose ends. And in the "winter" book Medraut seeks revenge for his mother's death - ultimately killing his entire family, brothers, nephew, father - no one is spared from the final reckoning. <br /><br />And in the end, Gwynhwyfar is left alone in a nunnery, forced to live out her days in exile - a punishment that seems a bit heavier now than it seemed to me when I was a teen. In her words - "It is a terrible thing to have worked the ruin of all one loved best, but it is worse to survive that ruin, and grow old, forgetting."<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="7164746613005370472" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


