    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_713858829" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/713858829" />
    <a title="Joy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1013741-joy"><img alt="Joy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1305829378p2/1013741.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/713858829?book_show_action=true">Sep 07, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joy" href="/user/show/1013741-joy">Joy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013741-joy?shelf=fantastic-fiction">fantastic-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013741-joy?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1013741-joy?shelf=alternative-history">alternative-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer713858829" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16571436954679782741">The last half of the Arthur&apos;s story is always hard for me to read. Some authors even put a happy spin on it. In this version the slow decline into chaos is narrated by Gwynhwyfar and her tragedy is made very real.<br/><br/>It is a much more sorrowful version, detailing the slow decline of the court and the painful awareness of the venom of Medraut, Arthur&apos;s bastard, is creating; but none can stop it honorably. Gwynhwyfar is a less romanticised/glamorized and much truer to what a Roman descended, educated </span>
  <span id="freeText16571436954679782741" style="display:none">The last half of the Arthur's story is always hard for me to read. Some authors even put a happy spin on it. In this version the slow decline into chaos is narrated by Gwynhwyfar and her tragedy is made very real.<br /><br />It is a much more sorrowful version, detailing the slow decline of the court and the painful awareness of the venom of Medraut, Arthur's bastard, is creating; but none can stop it honorably. Gwynhwyfar is a less romanticised/glamorized and much truer to what a Roman descended, educated woman from a powerful clan would be like. She works hard and does not live in a great castle!<br /><br />Many favorite items of the movies are also missing. The Knights (called Brothers instead) don't ride around in steel armor (not invented yet) and there is no Round Table or Lancerlot although Bedwyr plays his part. There is evil sorcery but it's hinted at it being a pack with Darkness while Camlann stands for the Light. The Christian aspect is downplayed. In fact the Church hates Arthur since he taxes the greedy bastards to help pay for the war to unite Britain. The political wrangling between Kings is also a major aspect of this version.<br /><br />I truly enjoyed this retelling for it's period authenticity, although it's not for those who want lots of battle and magic.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16571436954679782741" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

